722215f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 48th Street
722215f-a.text:
Fark Avenue, south from 48th Street, the Grand Central Yards,
before electrification, and the old Grand Central Station.
Behind the station towers thenbwly built Eotel Belmont at Park
Avenue and 42nd Street. To the right, is seen Tiffany House on
the east side of Madison Avenue between 45th and 44th Streets,
and behind it, the Hotel Manhattan, on N.W. corner of Madison
Avenue and 42nd Street. The small building on N.E. corner of
Madison Avenue and 45th Street is old Rail oad Y.M.C.A., where
Hotel Roosevelt will later stand. To extreme right are old
American Express buildinga, to be demolished about 1920.
1906.

722220f.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 48th Street
722220f.text:
'v.
Park Avenue, west side, from 48th to 50th Streets, during the middle
of the work of rebuilding the Grand Central Terminal and Yards.
The observer is near Lexington Avenue a little south of 49th
Street, which crosses the Upper Level yards at the right. The
nearest of the old buildings on the north side of 49th Street is
49 East 49th Street.
The yards have bcen rebuilt about as far west as what will be the
western side of Park Avenue when the tracks are covered over.
July, 1909.
Ewing Galloway.

722218f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 48th Street
722218f-a.text:
290 Park Avenue and Pierre's Restaurant, newly built, Park Avenue,
west side, from 48th to 49th Streets. The fence hides the
doorway of Pierre's.
On the vacant 1ot in the right foreground, the Park Lane Hotel
will rise in 1924.
1922.

722217f-a.text:
290 Park Avenue, west side, between E. 48th and 49th Streets.
Shown is Pierre'a Restaurant. Compare this view with that taken the

722219f-a.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 48th Street (East)
722219f-a.text:
Park Avenue, east side, from E. 48th (right) to 49th (left)
Streets, showing the newly completed Park Lane Apartment Hotel on
what twenty years prior was the Adams Express Company Building site.
The architects are Shulte and Weaver. Note at the left margin the
Railroad Y.M.C.A. at the N.E. corner of 49th Street. Ten years later
this will be razed for the block square site of the Waldorf Astoria
Hotel.
Summer 1924.
Cift of E.M. Jenks.
MAY BE RERODUCED.

722221f.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 48th Street
722221f.text:
Park Avenue, east side, between 49th and 48th Streets, showing the
new Park Lane Apartment Hotel, also a glimpse of the S.E. corner
of 48th Street vhere a building is under construction. In the
background the Hotel Shelton, on the east side of Lexington
AVenue, 1s shown.
Autumn 1924.
Amemiys, Photographer.
MAY BE REPRODUCED, with credit.

722216f.title: Manhattan: Park Avenue - 48th Street
722216f.text:
Park Avenue, east side, looking north from 48th Street, showing
the new Waldorf-Astoria, on the east side between 49th and 50th
Streets, opening October first.
Below it, between 48th and 49th Streets, stands the Park Lane
(1929); above, at 5lst Street, is the Ambasssdor (19204, and at
57th Street the Ritz Towers (1926).
The Queensboro Bridge is visible in right background.
September 1931.
International News Photos.
NO REPRODUCTIONS.
